<subSubSection pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,679,1488,1514]" box="[151,679,1488,1514]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,679,1488,1514]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" reason="4">
<taxonomicName authority="robustus Neave, 1910" authorityName="robustus Neave" authorityYear="1910" box="[151,679,1488,1514]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Platylesches" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="robustus" subSpecies="robustus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,679,1488,1514]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,522,1488,1514]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Platylesches robustus robustus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Neave, S. A." box="[529,679,1488,1514]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="2 - 86" refId="ref44641" refString="Neave, S. A. (1910) Zoological collections from Northern Rhodesia and adjacent territories: Lepidoptera Rhopalocera. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1910, 2 - 86, plates I - III, foldout map. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1910. tb 01885. x" type="journal article" year="1910">Neave, 1910</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1436,1559,1836]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
This species was described from Chambeshi (=Chambezi) valley, north-east 
<collectingCountry box="[1011,1099,1559,1584]" name="Zambia" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Zambia</collectingCountry>
, and the high plateau south of Lake Tanganyika (
<bibRefCitation author="Neave, S. A." box="[361,500,1595,1620]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="2 - 86" refId="ref44641" refString="Neave, S. A. (1910) Zoological collections from Northern Rhodesia and adjacent territories: Lepidoptera Rhopalocera. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1910, 2 - 86, plates I - III, foldout map. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1910. tb 01885. x" type="journal article" year="1910">Neave 1910</bibRefCitation>
) and is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[739,884,1595,1620]" name="South Africa" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">South Africa</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[923,1024,1595,1620]" name="Tanzania" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1081,1436,1595,1620]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Democratic Republic of Congo</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, W. H." box="[158,299,1631,1656]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" refId="ref42161" refString="Evans, W. H. (1937) A catalogue of the African Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum. British Museum (Natural History), London, UK, 212 pp, 30 plates." type="book" year="1937">Evans 1937</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kielland, J." box="[315,483,1631,1656]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" refId="ref43661" refString="Kielland, J. (1990) Butterflies of Tanzania. Hill House, Melbourne, Australia, 363 pp." type="book" year="1990">Kielland 1990</bibRefCitation>
), with separate subspecies in 
<collectingCountry box="[838,954,1631,1656]" name="Cameroon" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis box="[975,1025,1631,1656]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">villa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Evans, W. H." box="[1037,1181,1631,1656]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" refId="ref42161" refString="Evans, W. H. (1937) A catalogue of the African Hesperiidae indicating the classification and nomenclature adopted in the British Museum. British Museum (Natural History), London, UK, 212 pp, 30 plates." type="book" year="1937">Evans, 1937</bibRefCitation>
) and the 
<collectingCountry name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Republic of Guinea</collectingCountry>
(
<emphasis box="[251,288,1667,1692]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">fofi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen, T. B. &amp; Mei, M." box="[298,537,1667,1692]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="255 - 272" refId="ref43799" refString="Larsen, T. B. &amp; Mei, M. (1998) Butterflies from a Guinea savannah transition area, the Parc National du Haut Niger (Republic of Guinea), with description of a new subspecies of Platylesches robustus (Lepidoptera Hesperiidae). Bollettino della Societa Entomologica Italiana, 130 (3), 255 - 272." type="journal article" year="1998">Larsen &amp; Mei, 1998</bibRefCitation>
), which may well prove to be valid species (
<bibRefCitation author="Larsen, T. B. &amp; Mei, M." box="[1060,1294,1667,1692]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="255 - 272" refId="ref43799" refString="Larsen, T. B. &amp; Mei, M. (1998) Butterflies from a Guinea savannah transition area, the Parc National du Haut Niger (Republic of Guinea), with description of a new subspecies of Platylesches robustus (Lepidoptera Hesperiidae). Bollettino della Societa Entomologica Italiana, 130 (3), 255 - 272." type="journal article" year="1998">Larsen &amp; Mei 1998</bibRefCitation>
). TCEC has found this species at Mufindi and Kihansi in the Udzungwas, and the Usondo Plateau between Mpanda and Uvinza, 
<collectingCountry box="[246,349,1739,1764]" name="Tanzania" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
, and it is very common in the Mutinondo Wilderness, 
<collectingCountry box="[958,1047,1739,1764]" name="Zambia" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Zambia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="72" lastPageNumber="73" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1436,1559,1836]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<bibRefCitation author="Coetzer, A." box="[199,369,1775,1800]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" pagination="96 - 98" refId="ref41723" refString="Coetzer, A. (2006) Notes on the early stages of Platylesches robusta Neave, 1910 (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae). Metamorphosis, 17, 96 - 98." type="journal article" year="2006">Coetzer (2006)</bibRefCitation>
presents notes on the early stages of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Neave" authorityYear="1910" box="[793,928,1775,1800]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Platylesches" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[793,928,1775,1800]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Pl. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but this was based on a misidentification of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,274,1811,1836]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Platylesches" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moritili">
<emphasis box="[151,274,1811,1836]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Pl. moritili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(A. Coetzer pers. comm. 2010).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1435,1883,1980]" box="[151,286,1883,1908]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis box="[151,286,1883,1908]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Food plants</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="71.[151,1435,1883,1980]" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">
Woodhall (2005) suggested the food plant is probably 
<taxonomicName box="[786,981,1919,1944]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chrysobalanaceae" genus="Parinari" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="71" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="curatellifolia">
<emphasis box="[786,981,1919,1944]" italics="true" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Pa. curatellifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and this is the food plant upon which TCEC found this species in 
<collectingCountry box="[466,552,1955,1980]" name="Zambia" pageId="71" pageNumber="72">Zambia</collectingCountry>
and elsewhere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1436,151,644]" box="[151,279,151,176]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis box="[151,279,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Life history</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="72.[151,1436,151,644]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">
<bibRefCitation author="Congdon, C. &amp; Bampton, I. &amp; Collins, S." box="[151,401,188,213]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" pagination="160 - 164" refId="ref41841" refString="Congdon, C., Bampton, I. &amp; Collins, S. (2008) Early stages and larval shelters of some Platylesches Holland (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae). Metamorphosis, 19, 160 - 164." type="journal article" year="2008">
Congdon 
<emphasis box="[261,312,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">et al</emphasis>
. (2008)
</bibRefCitation>
describe the life history. In the early instars, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Neave" authorityYear="1910" box="[914,1049,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Platylesches" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[914,1049,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pl. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
makes shelters similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Evans" authorityYear="1937" box="[151,257,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Platylesches" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shona">
<emphasis box="[151,257,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pl. shona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(below). However, in the final instar, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Neave" authorityYear="1910" box="[690,825,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Platylesches" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robustus">
<emphasis box="[690,825,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Pl. robustus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
makes a chamber leaf shelter (
<figureCitation box="[1177,1289,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 80" captionStartId="72.[151,249,1212,1234]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,693,1195]" captionTargetId="figure-509@72.[151,1436,693,1195]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURE 80. Chamber leaf shelters of Platylesches robustus on Parinari curatellifolia, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, TCEC. 1, general view showing two leaves pulled together, with silken entrance to the right, 4 Dec 2007; 2, closer view from above, 9 Jan 2008; 3, as 2 from below; 4, opened shelter showing caterpillar in shelter, anterior view, 9 Jan 2008." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5268002" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5268002/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Figure 80</figureCitation>
) by securing the cut section of leaf to the leaf below, and then bringing a part of the cut leaf round to block off the front of the chamber. It then makes a circular silk-lined entrance hole, and creates an external tunnel of silk which curves round, blocking the line of sight to the inside of the chamber (
<figureCitation box="[866,982,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 80" captionStartId="72.[151,249,1212,1234]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,693,1195]" captionTargetId="figure-509@72.[151,1436,693,1195]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURE 80. Chamber leaf shelters of Platylesches robustus on Parinari curatellifolia, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, TCEC. 1, general view showing two leaves pulled together, with silken entrance to the right, 4 Dec 2007; 2, closer view from above, 9 Jan 2008; 3, as 2 from below; 4, opened shelter showing caterpillar in shelter, anterior view, 9 Jan 2008." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5268002" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5268002/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Figure 80</figureCitation>
). They make both left and right handed tunnels, contrary to the earlier suggestion that only right handed tunnels are made (
<bibRefCitation author="Congdon, C. &amp; Bampton, I. &amp; Collins, S." box="[1125,1370,367,392]" pageId="72" pageNumber="73" pagination="160 - 164" refId="ref41841" refString="Congdon, C., Bampton, I. &amp; Collins, S. (2008) Early stages and larval shelters of some Platylesches Holland (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae). Metamorphosis, 19, 160 - 164." type="journal article" year="2008">
Congdon 
<emphasis box="[1239,1292,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">et al</emphasis>
. 2008
</bibRefCitation>
). The chamber is lined with a generous layer of tough brownish silk, making it waterproof, if not bird-proof. Chambers are found among mature foliage well above the ground. The fully fed larva enters diapause for several months in the chamber before pupating, and final instar larvae from Mutinondo in 
<collectingCountry box="[980,1068,476,501]" name="Zambia" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Zambia</collectingCountry>
, collected in November, did not pupate until May and June the following year, indicating there is probably just one generation a year. 
<bibRefCitation author="Congdon, C. &amp; Bampton, I. &amp; Collins, S." pageId="72" pageNumber="73" pagination="160 - 164" refId="ref41841" refString="Congdon, C., Bampton, I. &amp; Collins, S. (2008) Early stages and larval shelters of some Platylesches Holland (Lepidoptera: Hesperiidae). Metamorphosis, 19, 160 - 164." type="journal article" year="2008">
Congdon 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">et al</emphasis>
. (2008)
</bibRefCitation>
suggested that the caterpillar (
<figureCitation box="[617,729,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 81" captionStartId="73.[151,249,1093,1115]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,177,1078]" captionTargetId="figure-244@73.[151,1436,169,1078]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURE 81. Final instar caterpillar of Platylesches robustus collected on Parinari curatellifolia, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, TCEC. 1, lateral view, 4 Dec 2007; 2, detail of head, anterior view, as 1; 3, dorsal view, as 1; 4, ready to pupate, 4 May 2008." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5268004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5268004/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Figure 81</figureCitation>
) is better able to defend itself against parasites and predators than a pupa would be. The pupa of this species (
<figureCitation box="[726,840,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 82" captionStartId="73.[151,249,1457,1479]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1220,1440]" captionTargetId="figure-248@73.[151,1436,1220,1440]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURE 82. Pupa of Platylesches robustus collected on Parinari curatellifolia, Mutinondo Wilderness, Zambia, 3 Feb 2008, TCEC. 1, dorsal view; 2, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5268006" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5268006/files/figure.png" pageId="72" pageNumber="73">Figure 82</figureCitation>
) is dark brown with paler bands on the abdominal segments.
</paragraph>
